    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1955-07-18T14:30:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1955-07-18T14:30:00-05:00" n="189"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d189">
                <head>189. Memorandum of the Conversation at the President’s Dinner, President’s
                    Villa, Geneva, July 18, 1955, 8:30 p.m.<note n="1" type="source"
                        xml:id="d189fn1">Source: Department of State, Central Files,
                        396.1–GE/7–2355. Top Secret. Drafted by <persName corresp="#p_BCEC1"
                            >Bohlen</persName> on July 23. For three other accounts of the dinner
                        conversations, see <ref target="#d187">Document 187</ref>, <ref
                            target="#d186">
                            <hi rend="italic">Supra</hi>
                        </ref>, and <ref target="#d188">
                            <hi rend="italic">infra</hi>
                        </ref>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <gloss target="#t_USDel1">USDEL</gloss>/<gloss target="#t_MC1"
                        >MC</gloss>/21</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Geneva</placeName>, <date
                            ana="#date_undated-inferred-from-document-head" calendar="gregorian"
                            type="conversation-or-meeting-date" when="1955-07-18T20:30:00+01:00"
                            >July 18, 1955, 8:30 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>During a dinner tonight, I told <persName corresp="#p_KNS1">Khrushchev</persName>
                    <note n="2" xml:id="d189fn2">
                        <persName corresp="#p_BCEC1">Bohlen</persName> was seated between <persName
                            corresp="#p_KNS1">Khrushchev</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_MLT1"
                            >Merchant</persName> to the right of Secretary <persName
                            corresp="#p_DAW1">Dulles</persName> at the table.</note> that I had been
                    absent from Moscow for over a month and that I had heard there had been
                    wide-spread rumors that he would take over the Premier-ship in addition to his
                    party duties after the Geneva Conference. <persName corresp="#p_KNS1"
                        >Khrushchev</persName> said he had heard these rumors which involved
                        <persName corresp="#p_BNA1">Bulganin</persName> replacing <persName
                        corresp="#p_MVM1">Molotov</persName> at the Foreign Office and another rumor
                    that he, <persName corresp="#p_KNS1">Khrushchev</persName>, was to take over the
                    Ministry of Agriculture. He said there was no truth whatsoever in either of
                    these rumors.</p>
                <p>I said to him there had been a good deal of discussion about the importance of
                    trust and confidence already at the conference and that I was, therefore,
                    prepared to accept his word but that it would be very unfortunate if it turned
                    out otherwise adding that, of course, I would not wish to pry into Soviet
                    internal affairs.</p>
                <p>He replied he could only repeat there was no truth in regard to these rumors. It
                    was, however, interesting that they had been brought very specifically to his
                    attention.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_BCEC1">Charles E. Bohlen</persName>
                        <note n="3" xml:id="d189fn3">Printed from a copy that bears this typed
                            signature.</note>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
